Why America Must Not Re-Elect President Bush
I have never been particularly politically engaged, but these are not normal times.
President George W. Bush endangers the security of the United States and the world and simultaneously undermines American values.
Because of my opposition to him, I was damned by Bush's campaign team.
President Bush ran in 2000 with a campaign program that promised a policy of "humility."
If he is re-elected, this will be a vote for the Bush doctrine of preemptive war—and the invasion of Iraq—and the world will have to live with the consequences.
By rejecting Bush's policies at the polls, America has a chance to regain the respect and support of the world.
The terrorist attacks of September 11, 2001, required a strong response.
However, they have also led to the suspension of the critical process so essential to democracy—the comprehensive and honest discussion of the pending problems.
Bush silenced the criticism by labeling it unpatriotic.
For 18 months following September 11, he managed to suppress any dissent.
In this way, he has led America in the wrong direction.
In fact, Bush played Osama bin Laden directly into his hands.
The invasion of Afghanistan—where bin Laden lived and Al Qaeda maintained its training camps—was justified.
The invasion of Iraq was not.
He was Bush's unintended gift to bin Laden.
Immediately following September 11, spontaneous expressions of sympathy towards America occurred all over the world.
These have given way to widespread bitterness.
More people than on September 11 are today willing to risk their lives to kill Americans.
Bush often claims that the terrorists hate Americans for who they are — a freedom-loving people — and not for what they do.
War and occupation, however, produce innocent victims.
We Americans count our fallen soldiers — more than 1,000 in Iraq.
The rest of the world also counts the Iraqis killed every day — perhaps twenty times as many.
Just as little was the torture of detainees in the Abu Ghraib prison the work of a few "rotten apples."
She was part of a system for the treatment of detainees established by Defense Secretary Donald Rumsfeld.
The international community condemns America, and our troops in Iraq pay the price for it.
Bush convinced people that America's security is in good hands by addressing the fears caused by the attacks of September 11.
In times of danger, people rally around their flag, and Bush exploited this by fostering a sense of threat.
His campaign is based on the assumption that people are ultimately not interested in the truth and will almost believe anything if it is repeated often enough.
There must be something wrong with America when we fall for this.
For example, approximately 40% of all Americans still believe that Saddam Hussein was involved in September 11, even though the September 11 Commission - appointed by Bush and chaired by a Republican - clearly determined that no such connection existed.
One would like to scream: "Wake up, America."
Do you not realize that we are being led by the nose?
The war in Iraq was based on false premises from the beginning to the end - if it ever came to an end.
It was a war of choice, not necessity.
More importantly, America was dragged into war under a pretext: no weapons of mass destruction were found, and the connection to Al Qaeda cannot be proven.
Bush then claimed that America went to war to free Iraq.
But no one can impose democracy by force.
Saddam Hussein was a tyrant, and the Iraqis—and the world—can be glad to be rid of him.
However, America had a duty to ensure justice and order; instead, we stood idly by as Baghdad and other cities were looted.
If we had truly been concerned about the Iraqi people, we would have had to deploy a larger number of troops for the occupation.
We would have had not only to protect the Ministry of Oil, but also other ministries, museums, and hospitals.
Worse still: Where American soldiers encountered resistance, they employed methods—such as entering private homes and mistreating prisoners—that pushed the population around and humiliated them, thereby inciting bitterness and anger.
The missteps and backtracking of the Bush administration are numerous.
First, the Iraqi army was dissolved, then America tried to restore it.
First, the United States tried to eliminate the Baathists, then America sought their help.
When the uprisings could no longer be contained, America installed an Iraqi government.
The man chosen as their leader was a CIA protegé with a reputation as a "strong man"—a far from democratic decision.
Despite the efforts of Bush's campaign team to spin the situation, the situation in Iraq remains bleak.
A large portion of the western part of the country was left to the insurgents. The prospects for holding free and fair elections in January are rapidly diminishing.
Civil war threatens.
Bush's war in Iraq has also inflicted incalculable damage on America, weakened its military strength, and undermined the morale of the troops.
Before the war, America could project an overwhelming sense of strength.
Not anymore.
Afghanistan slips from control.
North Korea, Iran, Pakistan, and other countries are pursuing nuclear programs with renewed vigor.
One can criticize the Bush administration on many other political issues, but none of them is as significant as Iraq.
The cost of the war has so far reached nearly $200 billion and will continue to rise, because the invasion of Iraq was much easier than the withdrawal will be.
Bush taunted John Kerry, asking him to explain what he would do differently.
Kerry replied that he would have done everything differently and that he would be in a better position to free us from our entanglement.
But it will not be easy for him either, because America is stuck in a swamp.
Leading military experts and diplomats urgently warned Bush not to invade Iraq.
He ignored them.
He suppressed the critical process, arguing that any criticism of the commanding general endangered the US troops.
But this is Bush's war, and he should be held accountable for it.
The Americans should take a moment and ask themselves: To whom do we owe this mess?
A moment of reflection would raise another question: Is Bush's cowboy demeanor qualified to remain America's commanding general?
